entry.title: [css-scroll-snap-2] Implement snapchanged for user scrolls
entry.content:
snapchanged[1] (explainer[2]) should fire when a scroller snaps to a

different set of elements than it was previously snapped to.

This pull request[3] will copy the details from the explainer to the

spec.



This patch implements snapchanged for user scrolls.



kSnappedToTolerance is increased to 1.0 because there appear to be

some differences between the way that fractional snap offsets are

handled in cc versus in blink. E.g. when snapping to a target,

blink may round a fractional offset down to the nearest integer

while cc may round it up as in this codepen[4] where a keyboard

scroll snap ends at 134px while a wheel scroll ends at

135px when snapping to the lower box.

Context:

https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/cxx/c/nBD_1LaanTc/m/ghh-ZZhWAwAJ?utm_medium=email&utm_source=footer



As of https://crrev.com/1204351, absl::optional is now a type alias for

std::optional. We should migrate toward it.



Script:

```

function replace {

echo "Replacing $1 by $2"

git grep -l "$1" \

| cut -f1 -d: \

| sort \

| uniq \

| grep "^ui/" \

| grep \

-e "\.h" \

-e "\.cc" \

-e "\.mm" \

-e "\.py" \

| xargs sed -i "s/$1/$2/g"

}



replace "absl::optional" "std::optional"

replace "absl::make_optional" "std::make_optional"

replace "absl::nullopt" "std::nullopt"

replace "absl::in_place" "std::in_place"

replace "absl::in_place_t" "std::in_place_t"
```

> [SHv2] Run PasswordStatusCheckService on browser startup

>

> This CL makes PasswordStatusCheckService be created at browser startup.

> There were couple of different issues:

>

> 1) To handle ScopedObserver destruction, OnBulkCheckServiceShutDown is

> added to both PasswordCheckDelegate and PasswordStatusCheckService.

> As A result, whenever bulk leak service shut down, both stop observing

> it.

>

> 2) Replaced is_update_credential_count_pending_ with

> running_update_credential_count_ to control killing infra based on

> the number of running checks.

>

> 3) Marked ServiceIsNULLWhileTesting is true to adapt the behavior of

> AccountPasswordStore. AccountPasswordStoreFactory class also set

> ServiceIsNULLWhileTesting to true.

>

> 4) Updated SafetyHubHandlerTest by creating a testing factory for

> PasswordStatusCheckService.

>

> 5) Added RunUntilIdle to SingleClientNigoriWithWebApiTests to provide

> enough time to PasswordStatusCheckService to shutdown infra. Otherwise,

> there were a few dangling pointers in BulkLeakCheckServiceAdapter.

>

> 6) Handled profile_store being empty case in PasswordStatusCheckService

> to prevent crashes when password store is not enabled.

entry.title: Update field types in WebView with a best-effort approach.
entry.content:
Previous behavior:

-If FormDataAndroid and FormStructure have different number of fields,

do not update anything.

-Assert that FormDataAndroid and FormStructure have same fields and same

ordering of those fields.



Behavior as of this CL:

-Updates all fields that can be found in both FormDataAndroid and

FormStructure, and skip the remaining fields.



A field that is in FormDataAndroid but not in FormStructure is a field

that was removed by an extraction that WebView is still unaware of.



A field that is in FormStructure but not in FormDataAndroid is a field

that was added by an extraction that WebView is still unaware of.

entry.title: Fix invalid pointer casts in third_party/lzma_sdk
entry.content:
lzma_sdk, like a lot of C projects, tries to optimize loading uint32 or

uint64 from byte buffers by casting pointers, when the target

architecture's endianness matches. This is not actually allowed, for two

reasons:



First, strict aliasing forbids pretty much all forms of type punning

here. Chromium builds with -fno-strict-aliasing, so this is moot, but

formally the C spec does not permit this.



Second, C forbids casting pointers that are not incorrectly aligned. So

even if the target architecture supports unaligned loads, one can never

create an unaligned uint32_t*, etc.



Instead, such loads should be done either with memcpy, or with

endian-independent code with shifts and whatnot. Any compiler worth its

salt[*] should then be able to optimize that code into the appropriate

load instruction if the target architecture supports it. Since lzma_sdk

already had endian-independent fallback code, just add a patch to use

it.



[*] Clang and GCC can optimize all of these just fine. MSVC is not very

good and cannot optimize the shifts. Projects that support MSVC should

ideally do this with a memcpy and a shift. Fortunately, we do not need

to support MSVC, so this is moot for us.

entry.title: Chrome for Testing: Introduce --disable-infobars switch
entry.content:
This gives developers and testers the ability to disable / hide infobars

via a command-line flag, without incurring any risks to regular

end-users of Chrome.



This feature is similar to the "CommandLineFlagSecurityWarningsEnabled"

enterprise policy.



- Most infobars are not usually present in real-world scenarios

involving end-users, creating an unwanted difference between test &

actual scenarios.

- Infobars take up space on the screen and affect viewport size, not

just affecting the browser UI itself but potentially the layout of the

web page being tested as well.

- Infobars affect screenshots of the browser UI, including golden

screenshots from tests.

- Infobars negatively impact battery consumption & performance.

entry.title: [AF] Remove BAM::FillOrPreviewVirtualCardInformation.
entry.content:
Virtual credit cards are not persisted in Chrome. They differ from

other CC types by the record type field set to autofill::CreditCard.

Previously, that was done by `BAM::FillOrPreviewVirtualCardInformation`.

This CL factors out that complexity from BAM as part of the effort to

simplify its API.



`BAM::FillOrPreviewVirtualCardInformation` was used from:

* AutofillExternalDelegate

* TouchToFillDelegateAndroidImpl

* Tests

CL, it should always store the token no matter

unloading its iframe.

entry.content:
Currently, promise icons are generated when we install non-launchable

ARC packages but they are not deleted when the installation completes.

This is because even though the installation is a success, it never

produces a launchable app to remove the promise icon with.



Hence, this change checks whether the installed ARC package is

launchable and marks the promise app as kCancelled when there is no

installed app to replace it. This will then correctly remove the

promise icon when the package installation completes.

entry.title: Account for document.head() returning null
entry.content:
It is possible for document.head() to return null. Most other call sites

check for this. Add the missing check here. This was causing UBSan

failures in DocumentLoaderTest.



There seem to be a few of these in Blink. Blink likes to use references

when it believes fields are non-null. Tracking non-null pointers is

good, but Blink seems to constantly dereference its nullable pointers

without null checks. The point of categorizing things is to force you to

check for the null on the transition from nullable to non-nullable, but

Blink's coding patterns seem not to do this.
